[1] Spain, Andalusia, serotype 4, ovine
Date: Sat 11 Oct 2014
Source: Huelva Informacion [in Spanish, machine trans., summ., edited]
http://www.huelvainformacion.es/article/provincia/1875145/brote/lengua/azul/afecta/menos/explotaciones/andaluzas.html


The Andalusian Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Rural Development, Elena Viboras, said yesterday [10 Oct 2014] that the bluetongue disease outbreaks that have been detected in the community [Andalusia] and resulted in imposed restrictions on the movement of sheep in the provinces of Cadiz, Cordoba, Malaga, Huelva and Sevilla, have affected at least 25 farms "and possibly some more," -- but the outbreak is "controlled."

The Minister urged the population to be "calm" because, she as she recalled, it is "an infectious disease caused by a mosquito" but "it does not involve risk of transmission to humans, affecting only animals," and also because "the serotype has been found to be 4, which is less aggressive."

The minister reported that the 1st outbreak was reported in the municipality of Fuente Palmera, Cordoba province, and was followed by outbreaks in about 25 other farms, not only in the province of Cordoba. Along these lines, she explained that the only Andalusian provinces currently not under sheep movement restrictions are Granada, Almeria, and Jaen, although she said that animals can indeed move "perfectly well" within each of the other 5 affected provinces. Viboras said that the regional government has held "meetings with agricultural organizations and farmers", who thus have "actual knowledge" of the situation, and "know exactly what to do." She explained that "there are currently no vaccines" but that with temperatures dropping, the disease will phase down. In areas which were vaccinated last year [2013], "the animals this year [2014] will not be affected". Meanwhile, Asaja [young farmers association] and COAG [Coordinator of Growers and Livestock Farmers Organisations] hope that the government will cover the costs of bluetongue vaccines, although both organisations underline the need for the EU to "get involved financially" and provide funding for these vaccines.

--
